<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-13T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-13T19:00:00-05:00" n="31" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">710.G/279: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-13T19:00:00-05:00">October 13, 1933—7
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>79. You may discreetly ask the Minister of Foreign Affairs whether,
                                in view of the continuance of the conditions that figured in
                                decision in May, 1932, to postpone the Conference,<note n="31" xml:id="d31fn31">See <ref target="frus1932v05#pg_1"><hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1932, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, pp. 1</ref> ff.</note> he does
                                not believe that it would be of interest to the other American
                                nations to have his views (as set forth in your telegram No. 86,
                                October 4, 1 p.m.) brought to their attention.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>